Diet.Source: Melletti & Meijaard 2017 Ecology, Conservation and Management of Wild Pigs and Peccaries
Diet.Notes: Diet includes a wide variety of foods, including roots & tubers, fruits & seeds, tender shoots & leaves, invertebrates, and small vertebrates. It is unclear how important invertebrates/vertebrates are to the diet. We assign Meat as 2, the most common value for suids in HerbiTraits.

Diet.Source: Kingdon 2015 The Kingdon Field Guide to African Mammals; Gagnon & Chew 2000 Journal of Mammalogy
Diet.Notes: Browsers and selective feeders. Gagnon & Chew report diet as 6% monocot, 94% dicot/fruit, so following HerbiTraits protocols we assign Graminoids as 0 and Browse/Fruit as 3.

Diet.Source: Kingdon 2015 The Kingdon Field Guide to African Mammals; Gagnon & Chew 2000 Journal of Mammalogy
Diet.Notes: Folivorous. Gagnon & Chew report diet as 5% monocot, 95% dicot/fruit, so following HerbiTraits protocols we assign Graminoids as 0 and Browse/Fruit as 3.

Diet.Source: Kingdon 2015 The Kingdon Field Guide to African Mammals; Gagnon & Chew 2000 Journal of Mammalogy
Diet.Notes: Folivorous. Gagnon & Chew report diet as 5% monocot, 95% dicot/fruit, so following HerbiTraits protocols we assign Graminoids as 0 and Browse/Fruit as 3.

Diet.Source: Kingdon 2015 The Kingdon Field Guide to African Mammals; Gagnon & Chew 2000 Journal of Mammalogy
Diet.Notes: Selective browsers, rarely eating grass. Gagnon & Chew report diet as 17% monocot, 83% dicot/fruit, so following HerbiTraits protocols we assign Graminoids as 1 and Browse/Fruit as 3.

Diet.Source: Kingdon 2015 The Kingdon Field Guide to African Mammals; Gagnon & Chew 2000 Journal of Mammalogy
Diet.Notes: Selective browsers. Gagnon & Chew report diet as 10% monocot, 90% dicot/fruit, so following HerbiTraits protocols we assign Graminoids as 0 and Browse/Fruit as 3.

Diet.Source: Kingdon 2015 The Kingdon Field Guide to African Mammals; Gagnon & Chew 2000 Journal of Mammalogy
Diet.Notes: Generally browsers. Gagnon & Chew report diet as 10% monocot, 90% dicot/fruit, so following HerbiTraits protocols we assign Graminoids as 0 and Browse/Fruit as 3.

Diet.Source: Kingdon 2015 The Kingdon Field Guide to African Mammals; Gagnon & Chew 2000 Journal of Mammalogy
Diet.Notes: Concentrate selectors, particularly of foliage. Gagnon & Chew report diet as 10% monocot, 90% dicot/fruit, so following HerbiTraits protocols we assign Graminoids as 0 and Browse/Fruit as 3.

Diet.Source: Prothero & Foss 2007 The Evolution of Artiodactyls
Diet.Notes: Tragulids are concentrate selectors, eating easily digestible foods such as fallen fruit and seeds, flowers, leaves, shoots, mushrooms, etc.
